{"author":{"id":"6fe2d7caea518c95e9f8542a2401015ca65f976dfdb6d4e3fa107b0f63c1f1c3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1490982302,"nonce":"BETveWRzlFjn7qj3wvJLbUYPhho=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDI5MDc4MDM1OA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1225#issuecomment-290780358"},"message":"Yes, that would be one use case, where you have Stringtie reconstructions in collections and as individual datasets. This currently won't work with the way the input selection is handled in the wrapper. \n\nIn a cleaner example, like your recent [RNAseq tutorial](https://galaxyproject.org/tutorials/nt_rnaseq/) where you have two collections, each representing an experimental condition (G1E and mega) that you would like to merge with a reference, you would only be able to input one or the other the way the input selection is set up. I see in your tutorial you combined the collections into one so you could use Stringtie-merge. If this wrapper used the \"Additional GTF inputs (Lists)\" feature that Cuffmerge uses, you could eliminate the additional step to combine the reconstructions upstream of Stringtie merge.","files":null}]}